=====================================================================
üìå SQL CONSTRAINTS (NOTES + EXAMPLES)
=====================================================================

SQL CONSTRAINTS are **rules** applied on table columns to:
‚úî Maintain data accuracy  
‚úî Prevent invalid data  
‚úî Ensure data integrity  

They control **what values are allowed** in a column.

====================================================================
BASIC DATABASE COMMANDS
--------------------------------------------------------------------
use world;
show tables;
====================================================================


====================================================================
# 1Ô∏è‚É£ PRIMARY KEY
====================================================================

------------------------------------------------------------
üîπ PRIMARY KEY
------------------------------------------------------------
DEFINITION:
Uniquely identifies each record in a table.

RULES:
‚úî Must be UNIQUE  
‚úî Cannot be NULL  
‚úî Only ONE per table  

EXAMPLE:
--------------------------------------------------------------------
create table student (
  id int primary key,
  name varchar(50)
);

------------------------------------------------------------


====================================================================
# 2Ô∏è‚É£ FOREIGN KEY
====================================================================

------------------------------------------------------------
üîπ FOREIGN KEY
------------------------------------------------------------
DEFINITION:
Creates relationship between two tables.
Refers to PRIMARY KEY of another table.

RULES:
‚úî Allows NULL  
‚úî Prevents invalid reference  

EXAMPLE:
--------------------------------------------------------------------
create table orders (
  order_id int primary key,
  customer_id int,
  foreign key (customer_id) references customers(id)
);

------------------------------------------------------------


====================================================================
# 3Ô∏è‚É£ UNIQUE
====================================================================

------------------------------------------------------------
üîπ UNIQUE
------------------------------------------------------------
DEFINITION:
Ensures all values in a column are different.

RULES:
‚úî Allows ONE NULL value  
‚úî Multiple UNIQUE allowed per table  

EXAMPLE:
--------------------------------------------------------------------
create table users (
  email varchar(100) unique
);

------------------------------------------------------------


====================================================================
# 4Ô∏è‚É£ NOT NULL
====================================================================

------------------------------------------------------------
üîπ NOT NULL
------------------------------------------------------------
DEFINITION:
Column must always have a value.

RULES:
‚úî NULL values NOT allowed  

EXAMPLE:
--------------------------------------------------------------------
create table employee (
  name varchar(50) not null
);

------------------------------------------------------------


====================================================================
# 5Ô∏è‚É£ CHECK
====================================================================

------------------------------------------------------------
üîπ CHECK
------------------------------------------------------------
DEFINITION:
Restricts values based on condition.

RULES:
‚úî Condition must be TRUE  

EXAMPLE:
--------------------------------------------------------------------
create table person (
  age int check (age >= 18)
);

------------------------------------------------------------


====================================================================
# 6Ô∏è‚É£ DEFAULT
====================================================================

------------------------------------------------------------
üîπ DEFAULT
------------------------------------------------------------
DEFINITION:
Sets default value if no value is provided.

EXAMPLE:
--------------------------------------------------------------------
create table account (
  status varchar(20) default 'active'
);

------------------------------------------------------------


====================================================================
# 7Ô∏è‚É£ AUTO_INCREMENT
====================================================================

------------------------------------------------------------
üîπ AUTO_INCREMENT
------------------------------------------------------------
DEFINITION:
Automatically increases numeric value for each new row.

RULES:
‚úî Used with PRIMARY KEY  
‚úî Starts from 1 by default  

EXAMPLE:
--------------------------------------------------------------------
create table product (
  id int primary key auto_increment,
  name varchar(50)
);

------------------------------------------------------------


====================================================================
SUMMARY
====================================================================
‚úî PRIMARY KEY ‚Üí unique + not null  
‚úî FOREIGN KEY ‚Üí table relationship  
‚úî UNIQUE ‚Üí no duplicate values  
‚úî NOT NULL ‚Üí mandatory value  
‚úî CHECK ‚Üí condition-based rule  
‚úî DEFAULT ‚Üí auto value if missing  
‚úî AUTO_INCREMENT ‚Üí auto number generation  

‚úî Used heavily in:
   ‚Ä¢ Database design  
   ‚Ä¢ Data validation  
   ‚Ä¢ Interviews  
   ‚Ä¢ Real-world applications  

END OF NOTES
====================================================================
